Check characteristics of diet PCs (derived without the diet trait)

Checked assumptions: -Diet (specific traits & diet patterns) associate with behavioral, SES and biological confounders. -Phenotypic diet-confounder associations are attenuated, after adjusting for dietPCs

  • Note: Not depicted, is an analyses of phenotypic correlations of diet-confounder associations: We saw that adjusting for dPCs attenuates the associations modestly, although not completely, suggesting there are unmeasured confounders or mediators.

Examine the effect of diet PC adjustment on causal effect estimates for variant-Food intake associations

Examine the magnitude (%) change in Beta coefficients with dietPC adjustment

In the plots of magnitude (%) Beta change after adjusting for hypothesized confounders/mediators, we see most substantial impact on Betas when adjusting for INCOME relative to other behavioral/lifestyle traits.

Examine the adjusted Beta coefficients after dietPC adjustment

Diet PCs were progressively introduced into the model and the resulting beta (5% CI) were plotted

Focus on adjusted Beta coefficients for each confounder, in referent models either without (Base GWAS covariates) or with (DietPCs) prior adjustment for diet PCs

Then, expand to looking across all confounders

Summary:

  • Note: adjusting for diet PCs attenuated all SNP-diet associations, but not to 0, indicating (1) remaining/unmeasured confounders/mediators explaining SNP-diet relations, or (2) possible direct effects of the SNP on diet, not explained by behavioral/lifestyle confounding or mediation.

  • We then compared the effects of dPC adjustment to confounder adjusment. We hypothesized that adjusting for each confounder will attenuate the associations to a modest degree; and that adjusting for an appropriate amount of dPCs will attenuate the associations to a greater degree, representing correction for behaviora/lifestyle confounders.
